## SOLID Principles

SOLID is a set of five design principles that help developers build software that is easy to maintain, extend, and refactor. Coined by Robert C. Martin (Uncle Bob), these principles are the bedrock of object-oriented design and appear in virtually every senior-level interview.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Without SOLID, codebases devolve into tightly coupled, rigid, and fragile systems. A single change in one module cascades across dozens of files. Testing becomes nearly impossible because everything depends on everything else. SOLID prevents this entropy by giving you clear rules about how classes and modules should relate to each other.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class UserService {
        +createUser(data)
    }
    class EmailService {
        +sendEmail(user)
    }
    class NotificationService {
        +notify(user)
    }
    class Database {
        <<interface>>
        +save(entity)
        +find(id)
    }
    class MySQLDatabase {
        +save(entity)
        +find(id)
    }
    class PostgresDatabase {
        +save(entity)
        +find(id)
    }
    UserService --> Database : depends on abstraction
    UserService --> EmailService : SRP separation
    Database <|.. MySQLDatabase : implements
    Database <|.. PostgresDatabase : implements
```

### S -- Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

A class should have only ONE reason to change. If a class handles user creation AND email sending AND logging, any change to the email system forces you to touch the user service.

**Red flag**: If you describe a class with the word "and" -- "it handles authentication AND logging AND reporting" -- it violates SRP.

### O -- Open/Closed Principle (OCP)

Software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification. You should be able to add new behavior without changing existing code. This is achieved through interfaces and polymorphism.

### L -- Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)

Subclasses must be substitutable for their parent classes without breaking the program. The classic violation: a Square class that extends Rectangle but breaks when you set width and height independently.

### I -- Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)

Clients should not be forced to depend on methods they do not use. Instead of one fat interface, create multiple focused interfaces.

### D -- Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)

High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions. This is the foundation of Dependency Injection.

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;

// === SRP: Each class has ONE responsibility ===
interface Database {
    void save(Map<String, String> entity);
    Map<String, String> find(String id);
}

class InMemoryDatabase implements Database {
    private final Map<String, Map<String, String>> store = new HashMap<>();

    @Override
    public void save(Map<String, String> entity) {
        store.put(entity.get("id"), entity);
        System.out.println("  [DB] Saved entity: " + entity.get("id"));
    }

    @Override
    public Map<String, String> find(String id) {
        return store.get(id);
    }
}

// ISP: Separate interfaces for separate concerns
interface Notifier {
    void notify(String userId, String message);
}

class EmailNotifier implements Notifier {
    @Override
    public void notify(String userId, String message) {
        System.out.println("  [Email] To " + userId + ": " + message);
    }
}

class SMSNotifier implements Notifier {
    @Override
    public void notify(String userId, String message) {
        System.out.println("  [SMS] To " + userId + ": " + message);
    }
}

// DIP: UserService depends on abstractions, not concretions
class UserService {
    private final Database db;
    private final List<Notifier> notifiers;

    public UserService(Database db, List<Notifier> notifiers) {
        this.db = db;
        this.notifiers = notifiers;
    }

    public void createUser(String id, String name, String email) {
        Map<String, String> user = new HashMap<>();
        user.put("id", id);
        user.put("name", name);
        user.put("email", email);
        db.save(user);
        for (Notifier n : notifiers) {
            n.notify(id, "Welcome, " + name + "!");
        }
    }
}

// OCP: Add new shapes without modifying existing code
interface Shape {
    double area();
}

class Circle implements Shape {
    private final double radius;
    Circle(double radius) { this.radius = radius; }
    @Override
    public double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }
}

class Rectangle implements Shape {
    private final double width, height;
    Rectangle(double w, double h) { this.width = w; this.height = h; }
    @Override
    public double area() { return width * height; }
}

class Triangle implements Shape {
    private final double base, height;
    Triangle(double b, double h) { this.base = b; this.height = h; }
    @Override
    public double area() { return 0.5 * base * height; }
}

class AreaCalculator {
    // OCP: This method NEVER needs to change when new shapes are added
    public static double totalArea(List<Shape> shapes) {
        return shapes.stream().mapToDouble(Shape::area).sum();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== SOLID Principles Demo ===");

        // DIP + SRP: Inject dependencies
        Database db = new InMemoryDatabase();
        List<Notifier> notifiers = List.of(new EmailNotifier(), new SMSNotifier());
        UserService service = new UserService(db, notifiers);

        System.out.println("\n--- SRP + DIP: User Creation ---");
        service.createUser("u1", "Alice", "alice@example.com");
        service.createUser("u2", "Bob", "bob@example.com");

        // OCP: Add new shapes without modifying AreaCalculator
        System.out.println("\n--- OCP: Area Calculation ---");
        List<Shape> shapes = List.of(
            new Circle(5),
            new Rectangle(4, 6),
            new Triangle(3, 8)
        );
        for (Shape s : shapes) {
            System.out.printf("  %s area = %.2f%n", s.getClass().getSimpleName(), s.area());
        }
        System.out.printf("  Total area = %.2f%n", AreaCalculator.totalArea(shapes));
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import Protocol


# === SRP: Each class has ONE job ===
class Database(Protocol):
    def save(self, entity: dict) -> None: ...
    def find(self, id: str) -> dict | None: ...


class InMemoryDatabase:
    def __init__(self):
        self._store: dict[str, dict] = {}

    def save(self, entity: dict) -> None:
        self._store[entity["id"]] = entity
        print(f"  [DB] Saved entity: {entity['id']}")

    def find(self, id: str) -> dict | None:
        return self._store.get(id)


# ISP: Separate protocol for notification
class Notifier(Protocol):
    def notify(self, user_id: str, message: str) -> None: ...


class EmailNotifier:
    def notify(self, user_id: str, message: str) -> None:
        print(f"  [Email] To {user_id}: {message}")


class SMSNotifier:
    def notify(self, user_id: str, message: str) -> None:
        print(f"  [SMS] To {user_id}: {message}")


# DIP: Depends on abstractions (Protocol), not concrete classes
class UserService:
    def __init__(self, db: Database, notifiers: list[Notifier]):
        self.db = db
        self.notifiers = notifiers

    def create_user(self, id: str, name: str, email: str) -> None:
        user = {"id": id, "name": name, "email": email}
        self.db.save(user)
        for n in self.notifiers:
            n.notify(id, f"Welcome, {name}!")


# OCP: Add new shapes without modifying existing code
class Shape(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self) -> float: ...


@dataclass
class Circle(Shape):
    radius: float
    def area(self) -> float:
        import math
        return math.pi * self.radius ** 2


@dataclass
class Rectangle(Shape):
    width: float
    height: float
    def area(self) -> float:
        return self.width * self.height


@dataclass
class Triangle(Shape):
    base: float
    height: float
    def area(self) -> float:
        return 0.5 * self.base * self.height


def total_area(shapes: list[Shape]) -> float:
    return sum(s.area() for s in shapes)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== SOLID Principles Demo ===")

    db = InMemoryDatabase()
    notifiers = [EmailNotifier(), SMSNotifier()]
    service = UserService(db, notifiers)

    print("\n--- SRP + DIP: User Creation ---")
    service.create_user("u1", "Alice", "alice@example.com")
    service.create_user("u2", "Bob", "bob@example.com")

    print("\n--- OCP: Area Calculation ---")
    shapes: list[Shape] = [Circle(5), Rectangle(4, 6), Triangle(3, 8)]
    for s in shapes:
        print(f"  {s.__class__.__name__} area = {s.area():.2f}")
    print(f"  Total area = {total_area(shapes):.2f}")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Building any non-trivial system. SOLID applies universally to OOP code. Especially critical in code that multiple developers touch, code that evolves over time, and code that needs automated testing.
- **Avoid when**: Writing throwaway scripts, prototypes that will be discarded, or very small programs where the overhead of abstractions exceeds the benefit. Do not over-engineer a 50-line script with 10 interfaces.

### Interview Questions

1. **"Explain SRP with a real example from your experience."** -- Describe splitting a monolithic service into focused services (UserService, EmailService, PaymentService).
2. **"What is the difference between SRP and ISP?"** -- SRP is about classes having one reason to change. ISP is about interfaces being focused so clients only depend on methods they use. SRP is class-level; ISP is interface-level.
3. **"How does DIP relate to Dependency Injection?"** -- DIP is the principle (depend on abstractions). DI is the technique (pass dependencies via constructor/method). DI implements DIP.

### Real-World Examples

- **Spring Framework**: Entire DI container is built on DIP. `@Autowired` injects interfaces, not concrete classes.
- **Django**: Middleware system follows OCP -- add new middleware without modifying existing ones.
- **Java Collections API**: `List` interface (ISP) -- you depend on `List`, not `ArrayList`. Swap implementations freely.

## Singleton Pattern

The Singleton pattern ensures a class has exactly ONE instance throughout the application's lifecycle, and provides a global point of access to it. It is probably the most well-known design pattern -- and also the most controversial.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Some resources are inherently shared and should not be duplicated: database connection pools, configuration managers, thread pools, caches, and logging services. Creating multiple instances of these would waste resources, cause data inconsistency, or create race conditions. Singleton guarantees exactly one instance exists.

However, Singleton is often considered an anti-pattern in modern development because it introduces global state, makes unit testing harder, and hides dependencies. Modern codebases prefer Dependency Injection containers that manage object lifecycles instead.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Singleton {
        -static instance: Singleton
        -Singleton()
        +static getInstance(): Singleton
        +operation()
    }
    class Client
    Client --> Singleton : getInstance()
    note for Singleton "Private constructor prevents\nexternal instantiation"
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.concurrent.*;

// === Approach 1: Eager Initialization (simplest, thread-safe) ===
class EagerSingleton {
    private static final EagerSingleton INSTANCE = new EagerSingleton();
    private final Map<String, String> config = new HashMap<>();

    private EagerSingleton() {
        config.put("db.host", "localhost");
        config.put("db.port", "5432");
        System.out.println("  [EagerSingleton] Instance created");
    }

    public static EagerSingleton getInstance() {
        return INSTANCE;
    }

    public String get(String key) {
        return config.getOrDefault(key, "not found");
    }
}

// === Approach 2: Double-Checked Locking (lazy, thread-safe) ===
class LazySingleton {
    private static volatile LazySingleton instance;
    private final List<String> logs = new ArrayList<>();

    private LazySingleton() {
        System.out.println("  [LazySingleton] Instance created");
    }

    public static LazySingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            synchronized (LazySingleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {
                    instance = new LazySingleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }

    public void log(String msg) {
        logs.add(msg);
    }

    public List<String> getLogs() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(logs);
    }
}

// === Approach 3: Enum Singleton (Joshua Bloch's recommended) ===
enum DatabasePool {
    INSTANCE;

    private final List<String> connections = new ArrayList<>();

    DatabasePool() {
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
            connections.add("Connection-" + i);
        }
        System.out.println("  [EnumSingleton] Pool created with " + connections.size() + " connections");
    }

    public String getConnection() {
        if (connections.isEmpty()) throw new RuntimeException("No connections available");
        return connections.remove(0);
    }

    public void releaseConnection(String conn) {
        connections.add(conn);
    }

    public int available() {
        return connections.size();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Singleton Pattern Demo ===");

        // Eager
        System.out.println("\n--- Eager Singleton (Config) ---");
        EagerSingleton config1 = EagerSingleton.getInstance();
        EagerSingleton config2 = EagerSingleton.getInstance();
        System.out.println("  Same instance? " + (config1 == config2));
        System.out.println("  db.host = " + config1.get("db.host"));

        // Lazy
        System.out.println("\n--- Lazy Singleton (Logger) ---");
        LazySingleton logger = LazySingleton.getInstance();
        logger.log("Application started");
        logger.log("User logged in");
        System.out.println("  Logs: " + LazySingleton.getInstance().getLogs());

        // Enum
        System.out.println("\n--- Enum Singleton (DB Pool) ---");
        String conn = DatabasePool.INSTANCE.getConnection();
        System.out.println("  Got: " + conn + ", available: " + DatabasePool.INSTANCE.available());
        DatabasePool.INSTANCE.releaseConnection(conn);
        System.out.println("  Released, available: " + DatabasePool.INSTANCE.available());

        // Thread-safety demo
        System.out.println("\n--- Thread Safety Test ---");
        Set<Integer> hashCodes = ConcurrentHashMap.newKeySet();
        ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
            pool.submit(() -> hashCodes.add(System.identityHashCode(LazySingleton.getInstance())));
        }
        pool.shutdown();
        try { pool.awaitTermination(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
        System.out.println("  Unique instances across 100 threads: " + hashCodes.size());
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
import threading


# === Approach 1: Thread-safe with double-checked locking ===
class DatabaseConnection:
    _instance = None
    _lock = threading.Lock()

    def __new__(cls):
        if cls._instance is None:
            with cls._lock:
                if cls._instance is None:
                    cls._instance = super().__new__(cls)
                    cls._instance._initialized = False
        return cls._instance

    def __init__(self):
        if self._initialized:
            return
        self._initialized = True
        self.host = "localhost"
        self.port = 5432
        self._queries: list[str] = []
        print("  [DatabaseConnection] Created")

    def execute(self, query: str) -> str:
        self._queries.append(query)
        return f"Executed: {query}"

    def query_count(self) -> int:
        return len(self._queries)


# === Approach 2: Module-level singleton (Pythonic) ===
class _AppConfig:
    def __init__(self):
        self.settings: dict[str, str] = {
            "debug": "true",
            "log_level": "INFO",
            "max_retries": "3",
        }
        print("  [AppConfig] Loaded settings")

    def get(self, key: str, default: str = "") -> str:
        return self.settings.get(key, default)

    def set(self, key: str, value: str) -> None:
        self.settings[key] = value


# Module-level instance -- Python imports are cached, so this is a singleton
app_config = _AppConfig()


# === Approach 3: Metaclass singleton ===
class SingletonMeta(type):
    _instances: dict[type, object] = {}
    _lock = threading.Lock()

    def __call__(cls, *args, **kwargs):
        if cls not in cls._instances:
            with cls._lock:
                if cls not in cls._instances:
                    instance = super().__call__(*args, **kwargs)
                    cls._instances[cls] = instance
        return cls._instances[cls]


class Logger(metaclass=SingletonMeta):
    def __init__(self):
        self.logs: list[str] = []
        print("  [Logger] Created via metaclass")

    def log(self, message: str) -> None:
        self.logs.append(message)

    def dump(self) -> list[str]:
        return list(self.logs)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Singleton Pattern Demo ===")

    # Thread-safe singleton
    print("\n--- Thread-safe Singleton (DB Connection) ---")
    db1 = DatabaseConnection()
    db2 = DatabaseConnection()
    print(f"  Same instance? {db1 is db2}")
    db1.execute("SELECT * FROM users")
    print(f"  Queries via db2: {db2.query_count()}")

    # Module-level singleton
    print("\n--- Module Singleton (Config) ---")
    print(f"  debug = {app_config.get('debug')}")
    app_config.set("debug", "false")
    print(f"  debug after change = {app_config.get('debug')}")

    # Metaclass singleton
    print("\n--- Metaclass Singleton (Logger) ---")
    log1 = Logger()
    log2 = Logger()
    log1.log("App started")
    log2.log("User logged in")
    print(f"  Same instance? {log1 is log2}")
    print(f"  All logs: {log2.dump()}")

    # Thread-safety proof
    print("\n--- Thread Safety Test ---")
    instances = set()
    def grab_instance():
        instances.add(id(DatabaseConnection()))
    threads = [threading.Thread(target=grab_instance) for _ in range(50)]
    for t in threads: t.start()
    for t in threads: t.join()
    print(f"  Unique instances across 50 threads: {len(instances)}")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: You truly need exactly one instance -- connection pools, hardware interface access, configuration that is loaded once at startup.
- **Avoid when**: You are using it just for convenience (global access). Prefer Dependency Injection. Singleton makes unit testing painful because you cannot substitute a mock easily. It hides dependencies -- code that uses `Singleton.getInstance()` does not declare its dependency in its constructor.

### Interview Questions

1. **"How do you make Singleton thread-safe in Java?"** -- volatile + double-checked locking, or use an Enum (Joshua Bloch's recommendation in Effective Java). Enum is serialization-safe and reflection-safe.
2. **"Why is Singleton considered an anti-pattern?"** -- Global mutable state, hidden dependencies, hard to test, violates SRP (manages its own lifecycle AND its business logic).
3. **"How does Singleton differ from a static class?"** -- Singleton can implement interfaces, be passed as a parameter, be lazily initialized, and be replaced with a subclass. Static classes cannot.

### Real-World Examples

- **Java Runtime**: `Runtime.getRuntime()` is a Singleton.
- **Spring Framework**: Beans are singletons by default (managed by the DI container, not the GoF pattern).
- **Python logging**: `logging.getLogger(name)` returns the same logger instance for the same name.
- **Android**: `Application` class is effectively a Singleton.

## Factory Pattern

The Factory pattern delegates object creation to a dedicated method or class, rather than using direct constructor calls. This decouples the client code from the concrete classes it instantiates.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Imagine a payment system that supports Stripe, PayPal, and Razorpay. Without Factory, your checkout code has `if/else` blocks sprinkled everywhere: `if (method == "stripe") new StripeGateway()`. Adding a new provider means hunting through every file. Factory centralizes creation logic in one place -- add a new provider in the factory, and all client code works automatically.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Notification {
        <<interface>>
        +send(message: String)
    }
    class EmailNotification {
        +send(message: String)
    }
    class SMSNotification {
        +send(message: String)
    }
    class PushNotification {
        +send(message: String)
    }
    class NotificationFactory {
        +create(channel: String): Notification
    }
    Notification <|.. EmailNotification
    Notification <|.. SMSNotification
    Notification <|.. PushNotification
    NotificationFactory --> Notification : creates
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;

// === Product interface ===
interface Notification {
    void send(String message);
    String getChannel();
}

// === Concrete products ===
class EmailNotification implements Notification {
    private final String recipient;
    EmailNotification(String recipient) { this.recipient = recipient; }
    @Override
    public void send(String message) {
        System.out.println("  [Email] To " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
    @Override
    public String getChannel() { return "email"; }
}

class SMSNotification implements Notification {
    private final String phoneNumber;
    SMSNotification(String phoneNumber) { this.phoneNumber = phoneNumber; }
    @Override
    public void send(String message) {
        System.out.println("  [SMS] To " + phoneNumber + ": " + message);
    }
    @Override
    public String getChannel() { return "sms"; }
}

class PushNotification implements Notification {
    private final String deviceToken;
    PushNotification(String deviceToken) { this.deviceToken = deviceToken; }
    @Override
    public void send(String message) {
        System.out.println("  [Push] To device " + deviceToken + ": " + message);
    }
    @Override
    public String getChannel() { return "push"; }
}

// === Simple Factory ===
class NotificationFactory {
    public static Notification create(String channel, String target) {
        return switch (channel.toLowerCase()) {
            case "email" -> new EmailNotification(target);
            case "sms" -> new SMSNotification(target);
            case "push" -> new PushNotification(target);
            default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown channel: " + channel);
        };
    }
}

// === Abstract Factory: UI Theme Example ===
interface Button { void render(); }
interface TextField { void render(); }
interface UIFactory {
    Button createButton(String label);
    TextField createTextField(String placeholder);
}

class DarkButton implements Button {
    private final String label;
    DarkButton(String label) { this.label = label; }
    @Override public void render() { System.out.println("  [DarkButton] " + label); }
}
class DarkTextField implements TextField {
    private final String placeholder;
    DarkTextField(String p) { this.placeholder = p; }
    @Override public void render() { System.out.println("  [DarkTextField] " + placeholder); }
}
class LightButton implements Button {
    private final String label;
    LightButton(String label) { this.label = label; }
    @Override public void render() { System.out.println("  [LightButton] " + label); }
}
class LightTextField implements TextField {
    private final String placeholder;
    LightTextField(String p) { this.placeholder = p; }
    @Override public void render() { System.out.println("  [LightTextField] " + placeholder); }
}

class DarkThemeFactory implements UIFactory {
    @Override public Button createButton(String label) { return new DarkButton(label); }
    @Override public TextField createTextField(String p) { return new DarkTextField(p); }
}
class LightThemeFactory implements UIFactory {
    @Override public Button createButton(String label) { return new LightButton(label); }
    @Override public TextField createTextField(String p) { return new LightTextField(p); }
}

public class Main {
    static void buildUI(UIFactory factory) {
        factory.createButton("Submit").render();
        factory.createTextField("Enter name...").render();
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Factory Pattern Demo ===");

        System.out.println("\n--- Simple Factory: Notifications ---");
        for (String[] r : List.of(
            new String[]{"email", "alice@example.com"},
            new String[]{"sms", "+1-555-0123"},
            new String[]{"push", "device-token-xyz"}
        )) {
            NotificationFactory.create(r[0], r[1]).send("Your order has shipped!");
        }

        System.out.println("\n--- Abstract Factory: Dark Theme ---");
        buildUI(new DarkThemeFactory());
        System.out.println("\n--- Abstract Factory: Light Theme ---");
        buildUI(new LightThemeFactory());
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
from dataclasses import dataclass


class Notification(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def send(self, message: str) -> None: ...

@dataclass
class EmailNotification(Notification):
    recipient: str
    def send(self, message: str) -> None:
        print(f"  [Email] To {self.recipient}: {message}")

@dataclass
class SMSNotification(Notification):
    phone_number: str
    def send(self, message: str) -> None:
        print(f"  [SMS] To {self.phone_number}: {message}")

@dataclass
class PushNotification(Notification):
    device_token: str
    def send(self, message: str) -> None:
        print(f"  [Push] To device {self.device_token}: {message}")


class NotificationFactory:
    _registry: dict[str, type[Notification]] = {
        "email": EmailNotification,
        "sms": SMSNotification,
        "push": PushNotification,
    }

    @classmethod
    def register(cls, channel: str, klass: type[Notification]) -> None:
        cls._registry[channel] = klass

    @classmethod
    def create(cls, channel: str, target: str) -> Notification:
        klass = cls._registry.get(channel)
        if klass is None:
            raise ValueError(f"Unknown channel: {channel}")
        return klass(target)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Factory Pattern Demo ===")

    print("\n--- Simple Factory: Notifications ---")
    for channel, target in [("email", "alice@example.com"), ("sms", "+1-555-0123"), ("push", "device-xyz")]:
        NotificationFactory.create(channel, target).send("Your order has shipped!")

    # Extensible factory
    print("\n--- Extensible Factory ---")
    @dataclass
    class SlackNotification(Notification):
        webhook_url: str
        def send(self, message: str) -> None:
            print(f"  [Slack] Webhook {self.webhook_url}: {message}")

    NotificationFactory.register("slack", SlackNotification)
    NotificationFactory.create("slack", "https://hooks.slack.com/xyz").send("Deployed!")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Object creation depends on runtime conditions (user config, environment, input data). When you want to decouple client code from concrete classes. When you need to support multiple product families (Abstract Factory).
- **Avoid when**: There is only one possible implementation -- Factory adds unnecessary indirection. If construction is simple (just `new Foo()`), do not wrap it in a factory.

### Interview Questions

1. **"What is the difference between Simple Factory and Abstract Factory?"** -- Simple Factory creates one product type. Abstract Factory creates families of related products that must be used together.
2. **"How does Factory support the Open/Closed Principle?"** -- New product types can be added by creating new classes and updating the factory, without modifying client code.
3. **"Factory vs Builder -- when would you choose each?"** -- Factory selects which class to instantiate. Builder constructs a complex object step by step. Use Factory when the type varies; use Builder when the construction process is complex.

### Real-World Examples

- **Java**: `Calendar.getInstance()`, `NumberFormat.getInstance()`, `DriverManager.getConnection()` -- all factory methods.
- **Spring**: `BeanFactory` and `ApplicationContext` are massive factory implementations.
- **Python**: `json.loads()` is a factory that returns dict/list/str depending on input.

## Builder Pattern

The Builder pattern constructs complex objects step-by-step. Instead of a constructor with 10 parameters (half of which are optional), you use a fluent API to set only what you need.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Consider creating an HTTP request: you need a URL (required), but method, headers, body, timeout, retry policy, and authentication are all optional. A constructor with all these parameters is unreadable: `new HttpRequest(url, "POST", headers, body, 30000, 3, authToken)`. Which parameter is which? Builder makes the code self-documenting.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class HttpRequest {
        -url: String
        -method: String
        -headers: Map
        -body: String
        -timeout: int
    }
    class HttpRequestBuilder {
        +url(url): HttpRequestBuilder
        +method(m): HttpRequestBuilder
        +header(k, v): HttpRequestBuilder
        +body(b): HttpRequestBuilder
        +timeout(t): HttpRequestBuilder
        +build(): HttpRequest
    }
    HttpRequestBuilder --> HttpRequest : builds
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;

class HttpRequest {
    private final String url;
    private final String method;
    private final Map<String, String> headers;
    private final String body;
    private final int timeoutMs;
    private final int maxRetries;

    private HttpRequest(Builder builder) {
        this.url = builder.url;
        this.method = builder.method;
        this.headers = Collections.unmodifiableMap(builder.headers);
        this.body = builder.body;
        this.timeoutMs = builder.timeoutMs;
        this.maxRetries = builder.maxRetries;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return String.format("%s %s\n    Headers: %s\n    Body: %s\n    Timeout: %dms, Retries: %d",
            method, url, headers, body, timeoutMs, maxRetries);
    }

    static class Builder {
        private final String url;
        private String method = "GET";
        private Map<String, String> headers = new LinkedHashMap<>();
        private String body = null;
        private int timeoutMs = 30000;
        private int maxRetries = 0;

        Builder(String url) {
            Objects.requireNonNull(url, "URL is required");
            this.url = url;
        }

        Builder method(String method) { this.method = method; return this; }
        Builder header(String key, String value) { this.headers.put(key, value); return this; }
        Builder body(String body) { this.body = body; return this; }
        Builder timeout(int ms) { this.timeoutMs = ms; return this; }
        Builder retries(int n) { this.maxRetries = n; return this; }

        HttpRequest build() {
            if (body != null && method.equals("GET")) {
                throw new IllegalStateException("GET requests cannot have a body");
            }
            return new HttpRequest(this);
        }
    }
}

class QueryBuilder {
    private String table;
    private final List<String> columns = new ArrayList<>();
    private final List<String> conditions = new ArrayList<>();
    private String orderBy;
    private Integer limit;
    private Integer offset;

    QueryBuilder select(String... cols) { columns.addAll(Arrays.asList(cols)); return this; }
    QueryBuilder from(String table) { this.table = table; return this; }
    QueryBuilder where(String condition) { conditions.add(condition); return this; }
    QueryBuilder orderBy(String field) { this.orderBy = field; return this; }
    QueryBuilder limit(int n) { this.limit = n; return this; }
    QueryBuilder offset(int n) { this.offset = n; return this; }

    String build() {
        StringBuilder sql = new StringBuilder("SELECT ");
        sql.append(columns.isEmpty() ? "*" : String.join(", ", columns));
        sql.append(" FROM ").append(table);
        if (!conditions.isEmpty()) sql.append(" WHERE ").append(String.join(" AND ", conditions));
        if (orderBy != null) sql.append(" ORDER BY ").append(orderBy);
        if (limit != null) sql.append(" LIMIT ").append(limit);
        if (offset != null) sql.append(" OFFSET ").append(offset);
        return sql.toString();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Builder Pattern Demo ===");

        System.out.println("\n--- HTTP Request Builder ---");
        HttpRequest getReq = new HttpRequest.Builder("https://api.example.com/users")
            .header("Accept", "application/json")
            .header("Authorization", "Bearer token123")
            .timeout(5000)
            .retries(3)
            .build();
        System.out.println("  " + getReq);

        HttpRequest postReq = new HttpRequest.Builder("https://api.example.com/users")
            .method("POST")
            .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
            .body("{\"name\": \"Alice\"}")
            .build();
        System.out.println("\n  " + postReq);

        System.out.println("\n--- SQL Query Builder ---");
        String q1 = new QueryBuilder()
            .select("id", "name", "email")
            .from("users")
            .where("active = true")
            .where("age > 18")
            .orderBy("created_at DESC")
            .limit(10)
            .build();
        System.out.println("  " + q1);
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from typing import Optional


@dataclass(frozen=True)
class HttpRequest:
    url: str
    method: str = "GET"
    headers: dict[str, str] = field(default_factory=dict)
    body: Optional[str] = None
    timeout_ms: int = 30000
    max_retries: int = 0


class HttpRequestBuilder:
    def __init__(self, url: str):
        self._url = url
        self._method = "GET"
        self._headers: dict[str, str] = {}
        self._body: Optional[str] = None
        self._timeout_ms = 30000
        self._max_retries = 0

    def method(self, m: str) -> "HttpRequestBuilder":
        self._method = m; return self
    def header(self, key: str, value: str) -> "HttpRequestBuilder":
        self._headers[key] = value; return self
    def body(self, b: str) -> "HttpRequestBuilder":
        self._body = b; return self
    def timeout(self, ms: int) -> "HttpRequestBuilder":
        self._timeout_ms = ms; return self
    def retries(self, n: int) -> "HttpRequestBuilder":
        self._max_retries = n; return self

    def build(self) -> HttpRequest:
        if self._body and self._method == "GET":
            raise ValueError("GET requests cannot have a body")
        return HttpRequest(
            url=self._url, method=self._method,
            headers=dict(self._headers), body=self._body,
            timeout_ms=self._timeout_ms, max_retries=self._max_retries,
        )


class QueryBuilder:
    def __init__(self):
        self._table = ""
        self._columns: list[str] = []
        self._conditions: list[str] = []
        self._order_by: Optional[str] = None
        self._limit: Optional[int] = None

    def select(self, *cols: str) -> "QueryBuilder":
        self._columns.extend(cols); return self
    def from_table(self, table: str) -> "QueryBuilder":
        self._table = table; return self
    def where(self, condition: str) -> "QueryBuilder":
        self._conditions.append(condition); return self
    def order_by(self, f: str) -> "QueryBuilder":
        self._order_by = f; return self
    def limit(self, n: int) -> "QueryBuilder":
        self._limit = n; return self

    def build(self) -> str:
        cols = ", ".join(self._columns) if self._columns else "*"
        sql = f"SELECT {cols} FROM {self._table}"
        if self._conditions:
            sql += " WHERE " + " AND ".join(self._conditions)
        if self._order_by:
            sql += f" ORDER BY {self._order_by}"
        if self._limit is not None:
            sql += f" LIMIT {self._limit}"
        return sql


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Builder Pattern Demo ===")

    print("\n--- HTTP Request Builder ---")
    req = (HttpRequestBuilder("https://api.example.com/users")
        .header("Accept", "application/json")
        .timeout(5000).retries(3).build())
    print(f"  {req}")

    print("\n--- SQL Query Builder ---")
    q = (QueryBuilder()
        .select("id", "name", "email")
        .from_table("users")
        .where("active = true").where("age > 18")
        .order_by("created_at DESC").limit(10).build())
    print(f"  {q}")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Object has 4+ parameters, especially optional ones. When construction involves validation logic. When you want immutable objects.
- **Avoid when**: Object is simple with 1-3 required parameters. Over-engineering a simple data class with a Builder adds needless complexity.

### Interview Questions

1. **"When would you use Builder over a constructor?"** -- When there are many optional parameters, when parameter ordering is error-prone, or when you need validation before construction.
2. **"How does Builder relate to immutability?"** -- Builder collects mutable state during construction, then creates an immutable product.
3. **"Builder vs Factory?"** -- Factory decides WHICH class to instantiate. Builder decides HOW to construct a complex instance of a known class.

### Real-World Examples

- **Java**: `StringBuilder`, `Stream.builder()`, `HttpClient.newBuilder()`, Lombok's `@Builder`.
- **Python**: Django's `QuerySet` is a builder -- `.filter().exclude().order_by()` chains.
- **OkHttp**: `Request.Builder()` is the canonical example in Android development.

## Observer Pattern (Pub/Sub)

The Observer pattern defines a one-to-many relationship between objects: when one object (the subject) changes state, all its dependents (observers) are notified automatically. This is the backbone of event-driven programming.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Without Observer, you need polling -- repeatedly checking "has anything changed?" This is wasteful and creates tight coupling. With Observer, the subject pushes updates to all registered listeners. The subject does not need to know who the listeners are -- just that they implement the listener interface.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class EventEmitter {
        -listeners: Map
        +on(event, listener)
        +off(event, listener)
        +emit(event, data)
    }
    class Listener {
        <<interface>>
        +handle(data)
    }
    class EmailListener { +handle(data) }
    class LogListener { +handle(data) }
    Listener <|.. EmailListener
    Listener <|.. LogListener
    EventEmitter --> Listener : notifies
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.concurrent.CopyOnWriteArrayList;
import java.util.function.Consumer;

class EventEmitter {
    private final Map<String, List<Consumer<Object>>> listeners = new HashMap<>();

    public void on(String event, Consumer<Object> listener) {
        listeners.computeIfAbsent(event, k -> new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>()).add(listener);
    }

    public void off(String event, Consumer<Object> listener) {
        List<Consumer<Object>> list = listeners.get(event);
        if (list != null) list.remove(listener);
    }

    public void emit(String event, Object data) {
        List<Consumer<Object>> list = listeners.get(event);
        if (list != null) for (Consumer<Object> listener : list) listener.accept(data);
    }

    public int listenerCount(String event) {
        return listeners.getOrDefault(event, List.of()).size();
    }
}

class OrderEvent {
    final String orderId;
    final String customerEmail;
    final double total;
    OrderEvent(String orderId, String email, double total) {
        this.orderId = orderId; this.customerEmail = email; this.total = total;
    }
}

class OrderService {
    private final EventEmitter events = new EventEmitter();
    public EventEmitter getEvents() { return events; }

    public void placeOrder(String orderId, String email, double total) {
        System.out.println("  [OrderService] Order placed: " + orderId);
        events.emit("order.placed", new OrderEvent(orderId, email, total));
    }

    public void cancelOrder(String orderId, String email) {
        System.out.println("  [OrderService] Order cancelled: " + orderId);
        events.emit("order.cancelled", new OrderEvent(orderId, email, 0));
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Observer Pattern Demo ===");
        OrderService orderService = new OrderService();
        EventEmitter events = orderService.getEvents();

        events.on("order.placed", data -> {
            OrderEvent e = (OrderEvent) data;
            System.out.println("  [Email] Confirmation sent to " + e.customerEmail);
        });
        events.on("order.placed", data -> {
            OrderEvent e = (OrderEvent) data;
            System.out.println("  [Inventory] Reserved items for " + e.orderId);
        });
        events.on("order.placed", data -> {
            OrderEvent e = (OrderEvent) data;
            System.out.printf("  [Analytics] Revenue: $%.2f%n", e.total);
        });
        events.on("order.cancelled", data -> {
            OrderEvent e = (OrderEvent) data;
            System.out.println("  [Inventory] Released items for " + e.orderId);
        });

        System.out.println("\n--- Placing Orders ---");
        orderService.placeOrder("ORD-001", "alice@example.com", 149.99);
        orderService.placeOrder("ORD-002", "bob@example.com", 299.50);
        System.out.println("\n--- Cancelling Order ---");
        orderService.cancelOrder("ORD-001", "alice@example.com");
        System.out.println("\n  Listener count: " + events.listenerCount("order.placed"));
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from collections import defaultdict
from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import Any, Callable


class EventEmitter:
    def __init__(self):
        self._listeners: dict[str, list[Callable]] = defaultdict(list)

    def on(self, event: str, listener: Callable) -> Callable:
        self._listeners[event].append(listener)
        return listener

    def off(self, event: str, listener: Callable) -> None:
        self._listeners[event] = [l for l in self._listeners[event] if l is not listener]

    def emit(self, event: str, data: Any = None) -> None:
        for listener in self._listeners[event]:
            listener(data)

    def once(self, event: str, listener: Callable) -> None:
        def wrapper(data):
            listener(data)
            self.off(event, wrapper)
        self._listeners[event].append(wrapper)


@dataclass
class OrderEvent:
    order_id: str
    customer_email: str
    total: float


class OrderService:
    def __init__(self):
        self.events = EventEmitter()

    def place_order(self, order_id: str, email: str, total: float) -> None:
        print(f"  [OrderService] Order placed: {order_id}")
        self.events.emit("order.placed", OrderEvent(order_id, email, total))


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Observer Pattern Demo ===")
    service = OrderService()

    @service.events.on("order.placed")
    def send_email(e: OrderEvent):
        print(f"  [Email] Confirmation to {e.customer_email}")

    @service.events.on("order.placed")
    def track_analytics(e: OrderEvent):
        print(f"  [Analytics] Revenue: ${e.total:.2f}")

    service.events.once("order.placed", lambda e: print("  [PROMO] First-order discount!"))

    print("\n--- Order 1 ---")
    service.place_order("ORD-001", "alice@example.com", 149.99)
    print("\n--- Order 2 (no promo -- once listener removed) ---")
    service.place_order("ORD-002", "bob@example.com", 299.50)
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Multiple objects need to react to state changes. Event-driven architectures. Decoupling producers from consumers.
- **Avoid when**: There is only one observer (direct method call is simpler). When event ordering matters and is hard to guarantee.

### Interview Questions

1. **"Observer vs Pub/Sub?"** -- Observer: subject directly notifies observers. Pub/Sub: uses a message broker as intermediary; publisher and subscriber do not know about each other.
2. **"How do you prevent memory leaks?"** -- Always provide an `off`/`removeListener` method. Use weak references in languages with GC. Unsubscribe in cleanup/destroy lifecycle hooks.
3. **"How does React relate to Observer?"** -- `useState` + re-rendering is Observer. Redux `subscribe()` is Observer.

### Real-World Examples

- **Node.js**: Built-in `EventEmitter` class.
- **DOM Events**: `addEventListener`/`removeEventListener`.
- **Spring**: `ApplicationEventPublisher`.
- **React**: `useState`, `useEffect`, Redux `subscribe()`.

## Strategy Pattern

The Strategy pattern defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one as a separate class, and makes them interchangeable at runtime. The client selects which algorithm to use without knowing its implementation details.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Without Strategy, you end up with massive if/else or switch statements. Adding a new algorithm means modifying existing code (violating OCP). Strategy lets you add new algorithms by creating new classes -- zero modifications to existing code.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class PricingStrategy {
        <<interface>>
        +calculatePrice(base, qty): double
    }
    class RegularPricing { +calculatePrice(base, qty): double }
    class BulkDiscountPricing { +calculatePrice(base, qty): double }
    class LoyaltyPricing { +calculatePrice(base, qty): double }
    class ShoppingCart {
        -strategy: PricingStrategy
        +setStrategy(s)
        +getTotal(): double
    }
    PricingStrategy <|.. RegularPricing
    PricingStrategy <|.. BulkDiscountPricing
    PricingStrategy <|.. LoyaltyPricing
    ShoppingCart --> PricingStrategy
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;

interface PricingStrategy {
    double calculatePrice(double basePrice, int quantity);
    String name();
}

class RegularPricing implements PricingStrategy {
    @Override public double calculatePrice(double basePrice, int quantity) {
        return basePrice * quantity;
    }
    @Override public String name() { return "Regular"; }
}

class BulkDiscountPricing implements PricingStrategy {
    @Override public double calculatePrice(double basePrice, int quantity) {
        double discount = quantity >= 100 ? 0.25 : quantity >= 50 ? 0.15 : quantity >= 10 ? 0.10 : 0;
        return basePrice * quantity * (1 - discount);
    }
    @Override public String name() { return "Bulk Discount"; }
}

class LoyaltyPricing implements PricingStrategy {
    private final int loyaltyYears;
    LoyaltyPricing(int years) { this.loyaltyYears = years; }
    @Override public double calculatePrice(double basePrice, int quantity) {
        double discount = Math.min(loyaltyYears * 0.05, 0.30);
        return basePrice * quantity * (1 - discount);
    }
    @Override public String name() { return "Loyalty (" + loyaltyYears + " yrs)"; }
}

class ShoppingCart {
    private PricingStrategy strategy;
    private final List<double[]> items = new ArrayList<>();

    ShoppingCart(PricingStrategy strategy) { this.strategy = strategy; }
    void setStrategy(PricingStrategy s) { this.strategy = s; }
    void addItem(double price, int qty) { items.add(new double[]{price, qty}); }

    double getTotal() {
        return items.stream().mapToDouble(i -> strategy.calculatePrice(i[0], (int)i[1])).sum();
    }

    void printReceipt() {
        System.out.printf("  Strategy: %s%n", strategy.name());
        for (double[] i : items) {
            System.out.printf("    $%.2f x %d = $%.2f%n", i[0], (int)i[1],
                strategy.calculatePrice(i[0], (int)i[1]));
        }
        System.out.printf("  TOTAL: $%.2f%n", getTotal());
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Strategy Pattern Demo ===");
        ShoppingCart cart = new ShoppingCart(new RegularPricing());
        cart.addItem(29.99, 5);
        cart.addItem(9.99, 20);

        System.out.println("\n--- Regular Pricing ---");
        cart.printReceipt();

        System.out.println("\n--- Bulk Discount ---");
        cart.setStrategy(new BulkDiscountPricing());
        cart.printReceipt();

        System.out.println("\n--- Loyalty (5 years) ---");
        cart.setStrategy(new LoyaltyPricing(5));
        cart.printReceipt();
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
from dataclasses import dataclass, field


class PricingStrategy(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def calculate(self, base_price: float, quantity: int) -> float: ...
    @abstractmethod
    def name(self) -> str: ...

class RegularPricing(PricingStrategy):
    def calculate(self, base_price: float, quantity: int) -> float:
        return base_price * quantity
    def name(self) -> str: return "Regular"

class BulkDiscountPricing(PricingStrategy):
    def calculate(self, base_price: float, quantity: int) -> float:
        discount = 0.25 if quantity >= 100 else 0.15 if quantity >= 50 else 0.10 if quantity >= 10 else 0
        return base_price * quantity * (1 - discount)
    def name(self) -> str: return "Bulk Discount"

@dataclass
class LoyaltyPricing(PricingStrategy):
    years: int
    def calculate(self, base_price: float, quantity: int) -> float:
        discount = min(self.years * 0.05, 0.30)
        return base_price * quantity * (1 - discount)
    def name(self) -> str: return f"Loyalty ({self.years} yrs)"

@dataclass
class ShoppingCart:
    strategy: PricingStrategy
    items: list[tuple[float, int]] = field(default_factory=list)

    def add_item(self, price: float, qty: int) -> None:
        self.items.append((price, qty))

    def total(self) -> float:
        return sum(self.strategy.calculate(p, q) for p, q in self.items)

    def receipt(self) -> None:
        print(f"  Strategy: {self.strategy.name()}")
        for price, qty in self.items:
            print(f"    ${price:.2f} x {qty} = ${self.strategy.calculate(price, qty):.2f}")
        print(f"  TOTAL: ${self.total():.2f}")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Strategy Pattern Demo ===")
    cart = ShoppingCart(strategy=RegularPricing())
    cart.add_item(29.99, 5)
    cart.add_item(9.99, 20)

    print("\n--- Regular ---")
    cart.receipt()
    print("\n--- Bulk Discount ---")
    cart.strategy = BulkDiscountPricing()
    cart.receipt()
    print("\n--- Loyalty (5 yrs) ---")
    cart.strategy = LoyaltyPricing(years=5)
    cart.receipt()
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Multiple algorithms for the same task and you want to swap at runtime. To eliminate if/else chains.
- **Avoid when**: Only one algorithm exists and will never change.

### Interview Questions

1. **"How does Strategy eliminate if/else?"** -- Each branch becomes a separate class implementing the strategy interface.
2. **"Strategy vs State?"** -- Both swap behavior at runtime. Strategy: client explicitly chooses. State: object transitions automatically.
3. **"In Python, when use a function instead of a class?"** -- When the strategy is a single stateless function. Python's first-class functions make simple strategies trivial.

### Real-World Examples

- **Java**: `Comparator` is a Strategy -- `Collections.sort(list, comparator)`.
- **Python**: `key` parameter in `sorted()` is Strategy.
- **Spring Security**: `AuthenticationStrategy` -- pluggable auth mechanisms.

## Decorator Pattern

The Decorator pattern attaches additional responsibilities to an object dynamically, by wrapping it in a decorator object that implements the same interface. Each decorator adds one behavior, and they can be stacked like layers.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Imagine a logging system: you want timestamps, JSON formatting, and filtering. With inheritance, you need `TimestampJsonFilteredLogger` -- an explosion of subclasses. With Decorator, compose behaviors: `new TimestampDecorator(new JsonDecorator(baseLogger))`.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class DataSource {
        <<interface>>
        +write(data: String)
        +read(): String
    }
    class FileDataSource { +write(data) +read() }
    class EncryptionDecorator { +write(data) +read() }
    class CompressionDecorator { +write(data) +read() }
    DataSource <|.. FileDataSource
    DataSource <|.. EncryptionDecorator
    DataSource <|.. CompressionDecorator
    EncryptionDecorator --> DataSource : wraps
    CompressionDecorator --> DataSource : wraps
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.Base64;

interface DataSource {
    void write(String data);
    String read();
}

class FileDataSource implements DataSource {
    private final String filename;
    private String content = "";
    FileDataSource(String filename) { this.filename = filename; }
    @Override public void write(String data) {
        this.content = data;
        System.out.println("  [File] Wrote to " + filename);
    }
    @Override public String read() {
        System.out.println("  [File] Read from " + filename);
        return content;
    }
}

abstract class DataSourceDecorator implements DataSource {
    protected final DataSource wrapped;
    DataSourceDecorator(DataSource wrapped) { this.wrapped = wrapped; }
}

class EncryptionDecorator extends DataSourceDecorator {
    EncryptionDecorator(DataSource wrapped) { super(wrapped); }
    @Override public void write(String data) {
        String encrypted = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(data.getBytes());
        System.out.println("  [Encrypt] Encrypted data");
        wrapped.write(encrypted);
    }
    @Override public String read() {
        String data = wrapped.read();
        System.out.println("  [Encrypt] Decrypted data");
        return new String(Base64.getDecoder().decode(data));
    }
}

class LoggingDecorator extends DataSourceDecorator {
    LoggingDecorator(DataSource wrapped) { super(wrapped); }
    @Override public void write(String data) {
        System.out.println("  [Log] Writing " + data.length() + " chars");
        wrapped.write(data);
    }
    @Override public String read() {
        System.out.println("  [Log] Reading...");
        return wrapped.read();
    }
}

// HTTP Middleware as Decorator
interface HttpHandler { String handle(String request); }

class AppHandler implements HttpHandler {
    @Override public String handle(String request) { return "Response for: " + request; }
}

class AuthMiddleware implements HttpHandler {
    private final HttpHandler next;
    AuthMiddleware(HttpHandler next) { this.next = next; }
    @Override public String handle(String request) {
        System.out.println("  [Auth] Checking credentials...");
        if (request.contains("unauthorized")) return "401 Forbidden";
        return next.handle(request);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Decorator Pattern Demo ===");

        System.out.println("\n--- Stacked Decorators: Log -> Encrypt -> File ---");
        DataSource source = new LoggingDecorator(new EncryptionDecorator(new FileDataSource("secret.dat")));
        System.out.println("\nWriting:");
        source.write("Sensitive data");
        System.out.println("\nReading:");
        System.out.println("  Result: " + source.read());

        System.out.println("\n--- HTTP Middleware ---");
        HttpHandler handler = new AuthMiddleware(new AppHandler());
        System.out.println("  Valid: " + handler.handle("GET /users"));
        System.out.println("  Denied: " + handler.handle("unauthorized GET /admin"));
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
import base64
import functools
import time
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod


class DataSource(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def write(self, data: str) -> None: ...
    @abstractmethod
    def read(self) -> str: ...

class FileDataSource(DataSource):
    def __init__(self, filename: str):
        self.filename = filename
        self._content = ""
    def write(self, data: str) -> None:
        self._content = data
        print(f"  [File] Wrote to {self.filename}")
    def read(self) -> str:
        print(f"  [File] Read from {self.filename}")
        return self._content

class EncryptionDecorator(DataSource):
    def __init__(self, wrapped: DataSource):
        self._wrapped = wrapped
    def write(self, data: str) -> None:
        encrypted = base64.b64encode(data.encode()).decode()
        print("  [Encrypt] Encrypted")
        self._wrapped.write(encrypted)
    def read(self) -> str:
        data = self._wrapped.read()
        print("  [Encrypt] Decrypted")
        return base64.b64decode(data.encode()).decode()

class LoggingDecorator(DataSource):
    def __init__(self, wrapped: DataSource):
        self._wrapped = wrapped
    def write(self, data: str) -> None:
        print(f"  [Log] Writing {len(data)} chars")
        self._wrapped.write(data)
    def read(self) -> str:
        print("  [Log] Reading...")
        return self._wrapped.read()

# Python @decorators (language feature)
def retry(max_attempts: int = 3, delay: float = 0.1):
    def decorator(func):
        @functools.wraps(func)
        def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
            for attempt in range(max_attempts):
                try:
                    return func(*args, **kwargs)
                except Exception as e:
                    if attempt == max_attempts - 1: raise
                    print(f"  [Retry] Attempt {attempt+1} failed: {e}")
                    time.sleep(delay * (2 ** attempt))
        return wrapper
    return decorator

def cache(func):
    memo = {}
    @functools.wraps(func)
    def wrapper(*args):
        if args not in memo:
            memo[args] = func(*args)
        return memo[args]
    return wrapper

@cache
def fibonacci(n: int) -> int:
    if n < 2: return n
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Decorator Pattern Demo ===")
    print("\n--- GoF Decorator ---")
    source = LoggingDecorator(EncryptionDecorator(FileDataSource("secret.dat")))
    source.write("Top secret")
    print(f"  Result: {source.read()}")

    print("\n--- Python @decorator ---")
    print(f"  fib(10) = {fibonacci(10)}")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Adding responsibilities dynamically. When subclassing creates class explosion. For cross-cutting concerns: logging, caching, auth, retry.
- **Avoid when**: Only one fixed combination is needed. When deep chains become hard to debug.

### Interview Questions

1. **"Decorator vs inheritance?"** -- Decorator: runtime, composable, OCP. Inheritance: compile-time, coupling, class explosion.
2. **"How does Decorator relate to OCP?"** -- Adds behavior without modifying the original class.
3. **"Python @decorator vs GoF?"** -- Python's wraps functions; GoF wraps objects. Same goal, different level.

### Real-World Examples

- **Java I/O**: `BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(new FileInputStream("file")))` -- classic chain.
- **Express.js/Django**: Middleware is Decorator.
- **Python**: `@functools.lru_cache`, `@retry`, `@login_required`.
- **Spring**: `@Transactional`, `@Cacheable` -- AOP decorators.

## Adapter Pattern

The Adapter pattern converts the interface of one class into another interface that clients expect. It allows classes with incompatible interfaces to work together -- like a power adapter for international plugs.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

You are integrating a third-party payment library, but its API uses different method names, parameter types, and return formats than your codebase expects. You cannot modify the third-party code. Adapter wraps the foreign interface and translates calls.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Target {
        <<interface>>
        +request(data): String
    }
    class Adaptee {
        +specificRequest(xml): int
    }
    class Adapter {
        -adaptee: Adaptee
        +request(data): String
    }
    Target <|.. Adapter
    Adapter --> Adaptee : wraps
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;

interface PaymentProcessor {
    boolean charge(String customerId, double amount, String currency);
    boolean refund(String transactionId, double amount);
}

class LegacyPaymentGateway {
    public int makePayment(int amountCents, String currencyCode, String clientRef) {
        System.out.printf("  [Legacy] Charging %d cents (%s) for %s%n", amountCents, currencyCode, clientRef);
        return 12345;
    }
    public boolean reversePayment(int txnNumber) {
        System.out.println("  [Legacy] Reversing #" + txnNumber);
        return true;
    }
}

class LegacyPaymentAdapter implements PaymentProcessor {
    private final LegacyPaymentGateway legacy;
    private final Map<String, Integer> txnMap = new HashMap<>();

    LegacyPaymentAdapter(LegacyPaymentGateway legacy) { this.legacy = legacy; }

    @Override
    public boolean charge(String customerId, double amount, String currency) {
        int cents = (int)(amount * 100);
        int txnId = legacy.makePayment(cents, currency.toUpperCase(), customerId);
        txnMap.put("TXN-" + txnId, txnId);
        System.out.println("  [Adapter] Mapped TXN-" + txnId);
        return txnId > 0;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean refund(String transactionId, double amount) {
        Integer legacyId = txnMap.get(transactionId);
        if (legacyId == null) return false;
        return legacy.reversePayment(legacyId);
    }
}

public class Main {
    static void processPayment(PaymentProcessor processor) {
        boolean success = processor.charge("CUST-001", 49.99, "usd");
        System.out.println("  Charge successful: " + success);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Adapter Pattern Demo ===");
        System.out.println("\n--- Legacy Payment Adapter ---");
        PaymentProcessor processor = new LegacyPaymentAdapter(new LegacyPaymentGateway());
        processPayment(processor);
    }
}
```

