### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Testable business logic. Might change databases. Centralize data access. Clean Architecture / DDD.
- **Avoid when**: Framework already provides repository abstractions (Spring Data) and another layer adds no value.

### Interview Questions

1. **"Why not call the DB directly?"** -- Untestable, coupled, duplicated queries. Repository centralizes and abstracts.
2. **"Repository vs DAO?"** -- DAO is DB-centric (maps to SQL). Repository is domain-centric (domain queries). Repository operates on entities; DAO on rows.
3. **"Spring Data JPA?"** -- Auto-generates repo implementations from interface definitions.

### Real-World Examples

- **Spring Data JPA**: `JpaRepository`, `CrudRepository`.
- **Django ORM**: `Model.objects` is a repository.
- **Android Room**: `@Dao` interfaces.
- **Mongoose**: Models act as repositories for MongoDB.

## Event Sourcing & CQRS

Event Sourcing stores the complete history of state changes as immutable events, rather than only the current state. CQRS separates read and write operations into different models optimized for each.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Traditional CRUD overwrites previous state -- you lose history. "Balance is $1000" tells you nothing about how it got there. Event Sourcing preserves the entire history. Combined with CQRS, you optimize reads and writes independently.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Event { <<interface>> +timestamp +type }
    class MoneyDeposited { +amount }
    class MoneyWithdrawn { +amount }
    class EventStore { +append(event) +getEvents(streamId) }
    class BankAccount { +apply(event) +rebuild(events) }
    Event <|.. MoneyDeposited
    Event <|.. MoneyWithdrawn
    EventStore --> Event
    BankAccount --> Event
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.time.Instant;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

sealed interface AccountEvent { String accountId(); Instant timestamp(); }
record AccountCreated(String accountId, String owner, Instant timestamp) implements AccountEvent {}
record MoneyDeposited(String accountId, double amount, String source, Instant timestamp) implements AccountEvent {}
record MoneyWithdrawn(String accountId, double amount, String reason, Instant timestamp) implements AccountEvent {}

class EventStore {
    private final Map<String, List<AccountEvent>> streams = new HashMap<>();
    public void append(String streamId, AccountEvent event) {
        streams.computeIfAbsent(streamId, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(event);
        System.out.println("  [Store] " + event.getClass().getSimpleName() + " -> " + streamId);
    }
    public List<AccountEvent> getEvents(String streamId) {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(streams.getOrDefault(streamId, List.of()));
    }
}

class BankAccount {
    private String id, owner;
    private double balance;
    private int txnCount;

    public static BankAccount rebuild(List<AccountEvent> events) {
        BankAccount acct = new BankAccount();
        for (AccountEvent e : events) acct.apply(e);
        return acct;
    }
    private void apply(AccountEvent event) {
        switch (event) {
            case AccountCreated e -> { this.id = e.accountId(); this.owner = e.owner(); this.balance = 0; }
            case MoneyDeposited e -> { this.balance += e.amount(); this.txnCount++; }
            case MoneyWithdrawn e -> { this.balance -= e.amount(); this.txnCount++; }
        }
    }
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }
    @Override public String toString() {
        return String.format("Account{%s, %s, $%.2f, %d txns}", id, owner, balance, txnCount);
    }
}

class AccountCommandHandler {
    private final EventStore store;
    AccountCommandHandler(EventStore store) { this.store = store; }
    public void createAccount(String id, String owner) {
        store.append(id, new AccountCreated(id, owner, Instant.now()));
    }
    public void deposit(String id, double amount, String source) {
        store.append(id, new MoneyDeposited(id, amount, source, Instant.now()));
    }
    public void withdraw(String id, double amount, String reason) {
        BankAccount acct = BankAccount.rebuild(store.getEvents(id));
        if (acct.getBalance() < amount)
            throw new IllegalStateException("Insufficient funds: " + acct.getBalance());
        store.append(id, new MoneyWithdrawn(id, amount, reason, Instant.now()));
    }
}

class AccountQueryHandler {
    private final EventStore store;
    AccountQueryHandler(EventStore store) { this.store = store; }
    public BankAccount getSummary(String id) { return BankAccount.rebuild(store.getEvents(id)); }
    public List<String> getAuditTrail(String id) {
        return store.getEvents(id).stream().map(e -> switch (e) {
            case AccountCreated a -> "Created for " + a.owner();
            case MoneyDeposited d -> String.format("Deposited $%.2f (%s)", d.amount(), d.source());
            case MoneyWithdrawn w -> String.format("Withdrew $%.2f (%s)", w.amount(), w.reason());
        }).collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Event Sourcing & CQRS Demo ===");
        EventStore store = new EventStore();
        AccountCommandHandler cmds = new AccountCommandHandler(store);
        AccountQueryHandler queries = new AccountQueryHandler(store);

        System.out.println("\n--- Commands ---");
        cmds.createAccount("ACC-001", "Alice");
        cmds.deposit("ACC-001", 1000, "Initial");
        cmds.deposit("ACC-001", 500, "Salary");
        cmds.withdraw("ACC-001", 200, "Rent");

        System.out.println("\n--- Queries ---");
        System.out.println("  " + queries.getSummary("ACC-001"));
        System.out.println("\n  Audit trail:");
        queries.getAuditTrail("ACC-001").forEach(e -> System.out.println("    " + e));

        System.out.println("\n--- Overdraft Test ---");
        try { cmds.withdraw("ACC-001", 99999, "Big purchase"); }
        catch (IllegalStateException e) { System.out.println("  Blocked: " + e.getMessage()); }
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from datetime import datetime
from collections import defaultdict

@dataclass(frozen=True)
class AccountCreated:
    account_id: str; owner: str; timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)

@dataclass(frozen=True)
class MoneyDeposited:
    account_id: str; amount: float; source: str; timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)

@dataclass(frozen=True)
class MoneyWithdrawn:
    account_id: str; amount: float; reason: str; timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)

AccountEvent = AccountCreated | MoneyDeposited | MoneyWithdrawn

class EventStore:
    def __init__(self): self._streams: dict[str, list] = defaultdict(list)
    def append(self, stream_id: str, event) -> None:
        self._streams[stream_id].append(event)
        print(f"  [Store] {type(event).__name__} -> {stream_id}")
    def get_events(self, stream_id: str) -> list: return list(self._streams[stream_id])

@dataclass
class BankAccount:
    id: str = ""; owner: str = ""; balance: float = 0.0; txn_count: int = 0
    def apply(self, event) -> None:
        match event:
            case AccountCreated(account_id=aid, owner=o): self.id = aid; self.owner = o
            case MoneyDeposited(amount=a): self.balance += a; self.txn_count += 1
            case MoneyWithdrawn(amount=a): self.balance -= a; self.txn_count += 1

    @staticmethod
    def rebuild(events: list) -> "BankAccount":
        acct = BankAccount()
        for e in events: acct.apply(e)
        return acct

class CommandHandler:
    def __init__(self, store: EventStore): self._store = store
    def create(self, id: str, owner: str): self._store.append(id, AccountCreated(id, owner))
    def deposit(self, id: str, amount: float, source: str):
        self._store.append(id, MoneyDeposited(id, amount, source))
    def withdraw(self, id: str, amount: float, reason: str):
        acct = BankAccount.rebuild(self._store.get_events(id))
        if acct.balance < amount: raise ValueError(f"Insufficient: {acct.balance}")
        self._store.append(id, MoneyWithdrawn(id, amount, reason))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Event Sourcing Demo ===")
    store = EventStore()
    cmds = CommandHandler(store)
    cmds.create("ACC-001", "Alice")
    cmds.deposit("ACC-001", 1000, "Initial")
    cmds.deposit("ACC-001", 500, "Salary")
    cmds.withdraw("ACC-001", 200, "Rent")
    print(f"\n  {BankAccount.rebuild(store.get_events('ACC-001'))}")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

- **Use when**: Audit trail required (finance, healthcare). Temporal queries needed. Domain is naturally event-driven. Read/write workloads differ dramatically.
- **Avoid when**: Simple CRUD suffices. Adds complexity: eventual consistency, event versioning, snapshots.

### Interview Questions

1. **"When Event Sourcing over CRUD?"** -- Auditability mandatory, temporal queries, replay for debugging, different read projections.
2. **"Biggest challenge?"** -- Event schema evolution. Historical events stay in old format. Need upcasting/versioning.
3. **"How does CQRS improve performance?"** -- Write side optimized for consistency. Read side uses denormalized views. Scale independently.

### Real-World Examples

- **Banking**: Every transaction is an event. Balance is a projection.
- **Git**: Commit history is event sourcing.
- **Kafka**: Append-only log consumers replay from any offset.
- **Axon Framework**: Full CQRS/ES for Java.

## Anti-Patterns & Code Smells

Anti-patterns are common solutions that appear to work but create more problems. Code smells are surface symptoms of deeper structural problems. Recognizing both shows engineering maturity.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

Knowing anti-patterns helps you avoid traps and review code effectively. Senior engineers are valued for what they prevent as much as what they build.

### UML / Structure

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class GodObject {
        +handleAuth()
        +processPayment()
        +sendEmail()
        +generateReport()
    }
    class AuthService { +authenticate() }
    class PaymentService { +process() }
    class EmailService { +send() }
    note for GodObject "Split into focused services"
    GodObject ..> AuthService : refactor
    GodObject ..> PaymentService : refactor
    GodObject ..> EmailService : refactor
```

### Java Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;

// === ANTI-PATTERN: GOD OBJECT ===
class BadAppManager {
    public boolean authenticate(String user, String pass) {
        System.out.println("  [GOD] Auth..."); return "admin".equals(user);
    }
    public void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("  [GOD] Payment: $" + amount);
    }
    public void sendEmail(String to) {
        System.out.println("  [GOD] Email to " + to);
    }
}

// GOOD: Focused services
class AuthService {
    public boolean authenticate(String user, String pass) {
        System.out.println("  [Auth] " + user); return "admin".equals(user);
    }
}

// === ANTI-PATTERN: TIGHT COUPLING ===
// BAD: Directly instantiates deps
class BadOrderService {
    public void placeOrder(String item) {
        // new MySQLDatabase().save(item); // Hard-coded!
        System.out.println("  [BAD] Hard-coded deps");
    }
}

// GOOD: DI
interface Database { void save(String data); }
interface Emailer { void send(String msg); }

class GoodOrderService {
    private final Database db;
    private final Emailer emailer;
    GoodOrderService(Database db, Emailer emailer) { this.db = db; this.emailer = emailer; }
    public void placeOrder(String item) { db.save(item); emailer.send("Order: " + item); }
}

// === MAGIC NUMBERS ===
class GoodCalc {
    private static final double TX_TAX_RATE = 0.0825;
    public double tax(double amount) { return amount * TX_TAX_RATE; }
}

// === LONG PARAM LIST -> Builder ===
class UserRequest {
    final String name, email;
    static class Builder {
        private String name, email;
        Builder(String name, String email) { this.name = name; this.email = email; }
        UserRequest build() { return new UserRequest(this); }
    }
    private UserRequest(Builder b) { this.name = b.name; this.email = b.email; }
    @Override public String toString() { return "UserRequest{" + name + ", " + email + "}"; }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Anti-Patterns & Code Smells Demo ===");

        System.out.println("\n--- God Object (BAD) ---");
        BadAppManager god = new BadAppManager();
        god.authenticate("admin", "pass");
        god.processPayment(99.99);
        god.sendEmail("user@example.com");
        System.out.println("  ^ All in ONE class!");

        System.out.println("\n--- DI Fix ---");
        Database mockDb = data -> System.out.println("  [MockDB] " + data);
        Emailer mockEmail = msg -> System.out.println("  [MockEmail] " + msg);
        new GoodOrderService(mockDb, mockEmail).placeOrder("Laptop");

        System.out.println("\n--- Builder Fix ---");
        System.out.println("  " + new UserRequest.Builder("Alice", "alice@test.com").build());

        System.out.println("\n--- Code Smells Cheat Sheet ---");
        System.out.println("  God Object      | Class does everything  | Split into services");
        System.out.println("  Long Method     | > 20 lines             | Extract methods");
        System.out.println("  Long Params     | > 3 parameters         | Use object/Builder");
        System.out.println("  Duplicate Code  | Same logic 2+ places   | Extract function");
        System.out.println("  Feature Envy    | Uses other's data      | Move method");
        System.out.println("  Magic Numbers   | Unexplained literals   | Named constants");
        System.out.println("  Tight Coupling  | Direct instantiation   | Dependency Injection");
    }
}
```

### Python Implementation

```python
from typing import Protocol
from dataclasses import dataclass

# GOD OBJECT (BAD)
class BadAppManager:
    def authenticate(self, user, password): print(f"  [GOD] Auth {user}")
    def process_payment(self, amount): print(f"  [GOD] Payment ${amount}")
    def send_email(self, to): print(f"  [GOD] Email {to}")

# GOOD: Focused
class AuthService:
    def authenticate(self, user, password): print(f"  [Auth] {user}")

# TIGHT COUPLING FIX: DI
class Database(Protocol):
    def save(self, data: str) -> None: ...
class Emailer(Protocol):
    def send(self, message: str) -> None: ...

class GoodOrderService:
    def __init__(self, db: Database, emailer: Emailer):
        self._db = db; self._emailer = emailer
    def place_order(self, item: str) -> None:
        self._db.save(item); self._emailer.send(f"Order: {item}")

# MAGIC NUMBERS FIX
TX_SALES_TAX_RATE = 0.0825
def calculate_tax(amount: float) -> float:
    return amount * TX_SALES_TAX_RATE

# LONG PARAMS FIX
@dataclass
class UserRequest:
    name: str; email: str; phone: str = ""

# DUPLICATE CODE FIX
def validate_email(email: str) -> None:
    if "@" not in email: raise ValueError(f"Invalid: {email}")

def register(email: str) -> None:
    validate_email(email); print(f"  Registered: {email}")

def subscribe(email: str) -> None:
    validate_email(email); print(f"  Subscribed: {email}")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Anti-Patterns Demo ===")

    print("\n--- God Object (BAD) ---")
    god = BadAppManager()
    god.authenticate("admin", "pass")
    god.process_payment(99.99)

    print("\n--- DI Fix ---")
    class MockDB:
        def save(self, data): print(f"  [MockDB] {data}")
    class MockEmail:
        def send(self, msg): print(f"  [MockEmail] {msg}")
    GoodOrderService(MockDB(), MockEmail()).place_order("Laptop")

    print("\n--- Code Smells ---")
    smells = [
        ("God Object", "Class does everything", "Split into services"),
        ("Long Method", "> 20 lines", "Extract methods"),
        ("Long Params", "> 3 parameters", "Use dataclass/Builder"),
        ("Duplicate Code", "Same logic 2+ places", "Extract function"),
        ("Magic Numbers", "Unexplained literals", "Named constants"),
        ("Tight Coupling", "Direct instantiation", "Dependency Injection"),
        ("Premature Optimization", "Optimize before profiling", "Profile first"),
        ("Golden Hammer", "Same tool for everything", "Right tool for job"),
        ("Cargo Cult", "Copy without understanding", "Understand WHY"),
    ]
    for name, sign, fix in smells:
        print(f"  {name:25s} | {sign:30s} | {fix}")
```

### When to Use vs When NOT to Use

This session is about problems to avoid, not a pattern to apply. Check during code reviews, refactoring sessions, and architecture decisions.

### Interview Questions

1. **"Top 3 code smells in reviews?"** -- God Object (SRP), duplicate code (DRY), tight coupling (DIP).
2. **"Premature Optimization?"** -- Optimizing before evidence of slowness. Rule: work, right, fast -- in that order.
3. **"Cargo Cult Programming?"** -- Copying patterns without understanding why. Microservices for a 2-person startup.

### Real-World Examples

- **God Object**: Early Django views handling auth + data + rendering + email.
- **Tight Coupling**: `new MySQLConnection()` scattered everywhere.
- **Premature Optimization**: Redis caching before 10 users.
- **Cargo Cult**: Kubernetes for 100 requests/day.
